We have a sorted array and need to 
(1) return the number of unique elements (length of array - duplicates found) as well as 
(2) modify the original array of nums so that only the unique elements are at the front of the array for the solution tester.

The algorithm simply compares each value in the nums array with the last known unique number which value is stored in the int  currentVal. 

When we compare the next element in the array with the currentVal (last unique value we found) and they are the same then we know we have another duplicate and can change the value of this number in the nums array to 101. As per constraints no numbers in nums are greater than 100, so any number 101 or higher will end up at the end of the array when resort later.

We loop through nums, either changing the value of duplicates to 101 or updating the int currentVal to represent the last known  unique value in nums. 

We keep comparing until we find a unique number at which point we update the current value we are comparing in the array as the new unique number. 

Once loop finished we SORT the nums array and all the 101s will endup at the end of the array and are ignored by the solution tester. We also return the size of the array less the number of duplicates we counted along the way (which is the number of unique numbers in nums). 

```
public class Solution {
    public int RemoveDuplicates(int[] nums) {
    int size=nums.Length;
    if (size<2) return nums[0];
    int currentVal=nums[0];
        int countDup=0;
        for (int i=0;i<size-1;i++)
        {
            if (currentVal == nums[i+1])
                {
                  // match
                    nums[i+1]=101; // will push it out of array when resorted
                    countDup++;
                }
                else 
                {
                    currentVal=nums[i+1];
                }
        }
        Array.Sort(nums);
        return size-countDup;

    }
}

